title: For Sale:  Hi-Standard Model "B" 1939 w/ Fink Holster
postcontent: Hi-Standard Model "B" Takedown System: Type II Calibre: .22LR Sights: Fixed Sights Serial #: 66XXX Year: 1939 Grips: Original Checkered Plastic "Ivory" Grips, No Monogram Weight: 1 lb. 14 ozs. List Price: $20 Extra Magazine: $1.50 original cost Holster: Fink Custom High Standard .22 Cal. Holster w/ Bird Design Fink Leather Shops Kansas City, MO This High Standard Model B was manufactured in 1939. The Model B is a self-loading, recoil operated, semi-automatic pistol that is chambered for the .22 Long Rifle cartridge. The pistol originally had a blued finish but it is starting to turn a brownish patina color now. This pistol has a 6 3/4 inch round barrel that is not easily removed (as seen on other High Standard pistols such as the Supermatic S-101). It is fed by a single column 10 round detachable box magazine. On the pistol's butt there is a European style heel magazine release. The pistol does not employ a slide hold open feature to inform the operator that the last round has been fired. There is a manual thumb safety lever located on the left side of the receiver and behind the grip panel. The High Standard Model B was first introduced in 1932 starting with serial number 5000 and it is basically the same pistol as the Hartford Arms 1925 automatic. The Model B was the company's first pistol design. The Model B along with later models such as the C, A, D, E and S designs have come to be known as the letter series. The company manufactured approximately 65,000 of these Model B pistols. The Model B was offered with either a 4 1/2 inch or a 6 3/4 inch barrel. The Model B and the Colt Woodsman look almost like identical pistols, although they are not. They were both derived however from the same earlier Browning design.

title: For Sale:  Savage 340D with rare Weaver scope mount and scope
postcontent: I've got a Savage 340D chambered in 222 Remington.  The rifle is in fantastic shape.  The Model 340 is an important rifle in Savage history as it was the first to use an external barrel nut - an convenient, innovative method of attaching the barrel to the receiver while ensuring proper headspace.  It is a design featured used in Savage rifles to this day.  The rifle's bolt uses controlled round feeding similar to a Mauser, it is smooth and reliable.  The rifle was equiped with iron sights, and the side mounted Weaver scope mount was an expensive addition even when the rifle was originally produced back in the 1950's.  The correct scope mount and magazine are not easy to find for these rifles these days, and mine has both.  The scope is also included.  I'm happy to answer any questions or forward more pictures.  Please respond with a phone number, I can either call or text you to facilitate this transaction.  Thanks.

postcontent: I bought this Smith & Wesson M&P Shield 9mm yesterday from a guy on Armslist, who bought it brand new in January at Academy. He only put about 200 rounds through it. The package includes the pistol, an 8-round magazine, a 7-round magazine, a plastic case, a lock and the original box and paperwork. I haven't shot it at all. It's just too small for me. I'm a big guy -- 6'2", 250 -- and my hand is too big for it, even with the 8-round magazine. This gun is designed for conceal-carry, and there aren't many handguns better for that than this one. It's less than an inch wide. It's light weight. It has a reputation for firing accurately without stovepipes or anything. It's got a unique stippling pattern and stands out with its gold highlights. If I were smaller, there's no way I'd let go of it.As is, my index finger doesn't sit properly on the trigger, and I have to contort my thumb in order to drop a magazine. I was really excited about buying this, so I'm bummed to admit it's not going to work for me. I'm not trying to get rich. I just want to get back what I paid for it yesterday. Not really interested in trades.I'm a solid guy and a public figure in OKC. I've been at the same media job for 16 years.
